1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:16,000
Today is June the 30th 2016 and we are in Santa Rosa, California.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:20,000
And this is David Klein from the History Department at Virginia Tech.

4
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:27,000
And also working with UNC, that is the Southern oral history program from the University of North Carolina,

5
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:32,000
on the Civil Rights History Project, which is a project of the Library of Congress,

6
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:37,000
and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

7
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Behind the camera today we have John Bishop of Media Generation and UCLA.

8
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:44,000
We're also joined today in the room by Guha Shankar of the Library of Congress.

9
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:50,000
And we have distinct pleasure of interviewing Big Man,

10
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:53,000
who is a veteran of the Black Panther Party.

11
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:56,000
And I'll ask you if you could introduce yourself,

12
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:04,000
and only time I'll coach you a complete sentence, I am, or my name is, and your name, and where you were born and when.

13
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Okay.

14
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Ready?

15
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:14,000
Okay, my name is Elbert "Big Man" Howard.

16
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:20,000
And I'm from Santa, New York, Tennessee, a native of Santa, New York, Tennessee,

17
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:28,000
but a long time resident of California, Northern California specifically.

18
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:35,000
And I wound up in Northern California after military service,

19
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:42,000
been in four years in the Air Force, and they decided to discharge me,

20
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:52,000
or I decided I wanted to be discharged in California because I loved it here, I loved the people.

21
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:57,000
And been a young man, I'm trying to find my way.

22
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:09,000
And so I ventured into Oakland, and started to sort of my, I guess, formal education,

23
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:15,000
or what I wanted out of education in Oakland and Merritt College.

24
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:19,000
Can I ask you first just a little bit about your childhood,

25
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,000
so you were born in Tennessee in one year?

26
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:25,000
1938.

27
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:29,000
And can you tell us a little bit about your family there, and growing up in the South?

28
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:34,000
Yeah, well, growing up, I don't know if it was typical or not,

29
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:39,000
but my father died, I never knew him.

30
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:44,000
All I knew was my mother, and aunts and cousins.

31
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:55,000
And I think that I was pretty much raised up as an only son by women", the aunts, my mother's sisters.

32
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:01,000
And then my cousins were, I guess you could say, my brothers and sisters really.

33
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:11,000
And I attended school and in high school.

34
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,000
And that sort of thing.

35
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:18,000
And all the schools were segregated schools at the time.

36
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:19,000
Right.

37
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:30,000
And I think long about 1954, they began to talk about integrating schools.

38
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:34,000
And I heard about that.

39
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:44,000
I told myself I have no problem going to school with white kids because I have my own set of friends

40
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:48,000
and living in my own set of society.

41
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:53,000
So I'm not up for that, but if it happens, it happens.

42
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:07,000
But I had teachers who I thought were concerned about me, who tried to teach me things that I needed to know to survive in a hostile world.

43
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:16,000
So, you know, I had no problem about wanting to integrate anything like that.

44
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:21,000
And I went through to the 11th grade.

45
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:27,000
And my mother being a single parent and everything.

46
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:32,000
I got to growing up and becoming an adult.

47
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:44,000
I figured one of the best ways for me to help support her and to develop myself was to join the military.

48
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:54,000
The air force after conversing with a lot of my friends who have been through basic training and all of that and come back.

49
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:58,000
And I picked their brains as to what it was all about.

50
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:03,000
And that's where I made my selection to choose the air force to go.

51
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:05,000
And what year was that?

52
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:08,000
That was when I was doing it in 1956.

53
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:12,000
I think I went there a few years after the Korean War.

54
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:15,000
Yeah, I missed that one.

55
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:18,000
Had you talked to other veterans who had been in that war or came back?

56
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:24,000
I had some relatives that had been to war and stuff like that.

57
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:30,000
And you know, the guys made a stay away from the army one day.

58
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:33,000
Why is that?

59
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:41,000
Because the army was the cattle pulled to going into combat and all that sort of thing.

60
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:48,000
And what I could find out about the air force is like you go in, you go through your basic training and everything.

61
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:51,000
And after that it was like a job.

62
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:55,000
You know, you went to work, you did what you were told.

63
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:59,000
And you had three meals a day at this place to live.

64
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:07,000
And you had freedom to explore the places that they sent you to.

65
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:12,000
So I felt very fortunate to be sent to Europe.

66
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:20,000
And I got to know Paris and Stockholm and cope in the hay again.

67
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:24,000
I visited all those places and met different people.

68
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:29,000
And to me it was a revelation.

69
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:34,000
And I opened into meet people of other culture.

70
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:51,000
And I realized that even though the people were called scathing or white, if you want to give it a color, they were very different than the white said I had a great fear of in the south that I grew up with.

71
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:57,000
So that was a revelation and a learning experience.

72
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:09,000
And to immerse myself and learn about their cultures, to learn how to drink wine and go to art museums and be talk stuff.

73
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:17,000
And you know, that was a good part of maturity, and maturing to me.

74
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:23,000
What about racial dynamics in the air force itself and seeing basic training but then when you got to Europe?

75
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:38,000
Well, it had it little nuances of segregation and even in France, which is a different environment.

76
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:45,000
And you had blacks hanging together because I don't know, our cultural similarities or whatever.

77
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:50,000
And you got along with the whites for the game.

78
00:07:50,000 --> 00:08:01,000
When it comes to stuff like economics, when it comes to promotions and stuff like that, you looked over, screwed over.

79
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:08,000
You just let it go by and enjoy yourself.

80
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:16,000
And learn what you wanted to learn and survive.

81
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:23,000
And to a great extent be happy without having to look over your show all the time.

82
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:29,000
Did you go in thinking that you would make a career of it or was this just a way out of where you were?

83
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:44,000
At the time, I thought it was kind of a way out to learn something different at the same time, to support my mother and a lot of it.

84
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:52,000
And so I knew I just got to check every month and I had food and shelter and everything for myself.

85
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:59,000
And you know, I think to me it was a pretty good deal.

86
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:03,000
I just had to put up with whatever I had to put up with.

87
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:05,000
And it wasn't all that strange.

88
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:10,000
It was abide by the rules and the routines and what you were told.

89
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:16,000
As long as you were there in the camp or whatever.

90
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:24,000
When you got your free time you had a chance to get out and explore and pretty much have a good time.

91
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:41,000
You know, go to jazz clubs and converse with jazz musicians who had left the US for the freedom of Europe to be able to practice their art and so forth.

92
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:47,000
And you know, it became an adventure for me.

93
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:52,000
Did you already have a love for jazz when you went over or did that develop in your own?

94
00:09:52,000 --> 00:10:06,000
I grew up, you know, the process of development from listening to the spirituals to old-time blues to R&B when that came in the focus.

95
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:12,000
And B-bop had come along. My brain was a progression.

96
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:24,000
You know, right on up until today, you know, look for the new sound and you know, adapt to it.

97
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:31,000
So you ended up after Europe went back to the United States in California?

98
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:33,000
Yeah.

99
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:44,000
And I can say I was still in the service on the air base in New Orleans, California.

100
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:45,000
It's a good thing.

101
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:48,000
And used to go into town in Oakland.

102
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:51,000
And that's why I met a lot of people.

103
00:10:51,000 --> 00:11:02,000
And you know, the very rich culture, you had blues and jazz and great soul food and friendly people.

104
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:13,000
And they took me under their wings, sort of speak, as a young trooper, and showed me around and stuff like that.

105
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:14,000
And I enjoyed that.

106
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:24,000
So when I got my discharge, I decided to take it here in Northern California and hang out in Oakland.

107
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:31,000
You know, and not really having any focus. That's what I really wanted to do.

108
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:37,000
I looked for a job at that time. It was really hard to come by.

109
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:49,000
Pretty much as you're out today. But I had a resource and education benefits from the Air Force.

110
00:11:49,000 --> 00:12:00,000
So I decided to enter into City College in Oakland and draw my GI bill.

111
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:08,000
It's up to to sustain me, you know, until I found some type of employment and all that.

112
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:21,000
And in the meantime, I began to study black history and stuff like that.

113
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:27,000
And I didn't have any real academic ambitions.

114
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:38,000
But I always thought that I wanted to be able to be able to write and express myself clearly.

115
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:55,000
So I took some courses in writing and stuff like that in school to try to develop writing skills, nothing professional just my own.

116
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:59,000
And I wanted to convey something to be able to do it.

117
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:04,000
And black history had been part of your schooling at all in Tennessee?

118
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:12,000
No. No. At that time, it was not even thought of.

119
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:19,000
So this was new material for you in some ways.

120
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:33,000
At Enrolling in Merritt College, I began to associate with other students who had, you know, similar interests.

121
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:37,000
And that's where I met Bobby Seale and Huey Newton.

122
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:52,000
And we used to, after our classes, with how we were in the rap sessions and talk about these things and talk about ways of dealing with them.

123
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:57,000
Because we had repression going on in Oakland police repression.

124
00:13:57,000 --> 00:14:01,000
And people getting killed by cops every week.

125
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:20,000
And we would kick around ways of dealing with that, you know, try to figure out a different way of approaching it as opposed to the civil rights and the non-violence and all that sort of stuff.

126
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:34,000
Because we knew what that was about. But we were trying to develop a new approach, you know, something progressive and revolutionary, if you will.

127
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:41,000
And so, you know, Bobby Seale and I want you to meet Huey.

128
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:47,000
And we were thinking of starting a new organization.

129
00:14:47,000 --> 00:15:07,000
And they started to develop the 10 point platform and program, which was, you know, the mandate, you know, if you will, that would differentiate us from other organizations.

130
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:20,000
Because they had other organizations that dealt with culture, you know, Swahili camps and learning language and stuff like that.

131
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:35,000
And we were more interested in trying to deal with combating the yields in the community on progressive and revolutionary level.

132
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:39,000
So what were some of the issues at the base of the 10 point platform?

133
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:46,000
We were on freedom. We want the power to determine our destiny, which is number one on the list.

134
00:15:46,000 --> 00:16:00,000
And we felt we were occupied by police forces, you know, doing the bidding of the rich politicians.

135
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:22,000
So we began to study things like the writings of Che Guevara and Mao Zedong, Kwame Nkrumah Malcolm X and all the revolutionary people around the world.

136
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:38,000
And we started to cherry pick some of their philosophies and ways of thinking and apply it to what we wanted to do.

137
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:49,000
We fully realized that we were not in China, we were not in Cuba. And we couldn't emulate anything that those people did.

138
00:16:49,000 --> 00:17:01,000
But we had to come up with our own approach utilizing what we could from these great people, you know.

139
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:09,000
And that's where we got a lot of our philosophy from.

140
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:16,000
Could I ask you to tell me just a little bit more about young Bobby Seale and young Huey Newton?

141
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:20,000
Well, they were like when you first met and started hanging out with these guys.

142
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:35,000
Well, with Bobby, I hung more with him than with Huey. He was always, you know, in and out sort of speak.

143
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:46,000
But, you know, he was, to me, very knowledgeable because he about the justice system because he had been through it.

144
00:17:46,000 --> 00:18:01,000
And whenever I had a case or some problem with the police, I could usually go to here and say, you know, I said I approached this and going to court and stuff like that.

145
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:08,000
So he knew, you know, how I should do that.

146
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:21,000
And so I got somebody to lie to him. But we never hung together except for having meetings as the organization began to come together and grow, you know.

147
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:34,000
Some more than then. But Bobby, to me, was had a great skill for organizing, you know.

148
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:42,000
And he had great ideas. And at the time, early on, a lot of them seemed very far fixed to me.

149
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:52,000
But I've always been a listener and try to internalize what I'm hearing, you know.

150
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:59,000
And put it in the locker for later references.

151
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:16,000
But we would get together with other kids on campus and we'd sit down and we would, you know, go back and forth about approaches and ways of solving problems and so forth.

152
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:28,000
And in the meantime, Bobby said we were starting a new organization and then they began to work on that 10-point platform program and reach it out, OK.

153
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:37,000
Who was an agent who pretty much grew up after he got out of that damn camp that they put his family in.

154
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:49,000
He began to live in the associate with the other poor and oppressed people in Oakland. I mean, black people.

155
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:59,000
So, you know, he used to hang and he worked with Bobby on that 10-point platform program.

156
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:15,000
And, you know, it just started to come together. Our ideas and so forth. And we began to talk more and more with more and more people.

157
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:24,000
And they said, yeah, you know, I can relate to these ideas and so forth.

158
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:35,000
What do we do next, you know. And it came together like pretty much like that.

159
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:43,000
Was there, I think, a particular incident with the police that sort of pushed you towards the group a little bit more?

160
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:46,000
Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. Tell us about that.

161
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:54,000
Because as I said, I enjoyed going out to Oakland to the Blues and Jazz clubs and so forth.

162
00:20:54,000 --> 00:21:05,000
And one night I was out at a club that Don Barksdale's was, we got to run a club with black ex-Baskabalt player.

163
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:13,000
And I think it was a little wrong when he was first coming on and getting popular.

164
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:22,000
Went out to see his show and me and my date and when it was over, we were leaving.

165
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:28,000
And it was drizzling outside. So I told my date wait here.

166
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:34,000
I'm going to go and get my vehicle on and I'll come back and pick it right in front of the club.

167
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:45,000
So I'll pull up in front of the club waiting for her to come out and the cops come up and start writing tickets.

168
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:54,000
Well, it wrote me a ticket and I looked at behind me and they didn't write the guy behind me one and the person they hit at me.

169
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:59,000
And I took offense because I had a brand new red pickup truck.

170
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:09,000
And I protested, I asked them, you know, why the hell am I getting a ticket and you're in writing these other people in here?

171
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:16,000
And it says, some smart and I say, well, fuck this, I'm taking off.

172
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:23,000
So I got my truck and took off and then here comes the game.

173
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:29,000
It boxed me in and took me in and I picked up to jail.

174
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:41,000
So from then on, I said, well, you know, I got to get involved with something that combats this kind of crap.

175
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:48,000
And this is what you were invited to talk about.

176
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:54,000
You know, I went to court and asked you to advise me and stuff.

177
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:05,000
And he went to court with me and the judge says, well, something that offended me and something like,

178
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:10,000
well, he's probably guilty, but I'm going to dismiss it.

179
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:16,000
In the meantime, the cops are sitting there in the court laughing and shit, you know.

180
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:21,000
And I got, you know, highly pissed off about that.

181
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:24,000
Anyway, dismiss the case.

182
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:33,000
So after that, I left and I took to very angry and I took to driving around in my pickup.

183
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:38,000
I had a rack put in the back of it and I put a legal shotgun in the back of it.

184
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:44,000
So I rode around and I'd say, well, you know, I'm as good as somebody red next to it right around like this.

185
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:49,000
And if I may go confront it, I'm going to defend myself, period.

186
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:56,000
So, you know, luckily, nothing happened and I didn't have to do that.

187
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:01,000
I continued to do that.

188
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:05,000
And, you know, as I was doing the party, I continued to do that.

189
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:09,000
And you all had researched and were aware that it's perfectly legal, right?

190
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:10,000
Oh, yeah.

191
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:11,000
Yeah.

192
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:23,000
And on a way to take Huey home after the court date, I asked him about the legalities of a car and a weapon in the car.

193
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:25,000
He called me on that.

194
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:29,000
That's why, you know, I was able to do that.

195
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:40,000
I knew that it was perfectly legal and it was a 12-gauge shotgun that I purchased.

196
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:48,000
And, you know, went from there.

197
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:55,000
So what were some of the first things that you all did?

198
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:01,000
In terms of work that you did with the party, I think, patrolling the police themselves.

199
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:04,000
Was that one of the things that you started to do?

200
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:09,000
Yeah, that happened a little bit later on.

201
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:20,000
And, you know, we began to get more members and we began to acquire more firearms and stuff.

202
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:28,000
And, you know, once again, consulting with Huey, he knew the law because he studied law and stuff.

203
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:32,000
And knew that we could do that legally.

204
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:43,000
And so we began to do that at night on the weekends when we knew the cops were patrolling our community.

205
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:59,000
And so we decided that we would get out and patrolling and not to confront them necessarily and engage in any battle.

206
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:07,000
But to teach people in the community that they had a right, they had rights.

207
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:17,000
And we would advise people when they would stop by the cops, we'd get out and observe the cops' so-called performing and duty.

208
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:22,000
And, if we were on the scene, they would not abuse the people.

209
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:28,000
They became more concerned with these young black people with guns.

210
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:37,000
And so we advised people that being arrested to go ahead and take their rest, don't resist.

211
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:44,000
And we're going to follow you down to the courthouse and we're going to bail you out.

212
00:26:44,000 --> 00:26:46,000
And we did that.

213
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:52,000
And people began to wonder who are these guys?

214
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:55,000
Why would they be doing that?

215
00:26:55,000 --> 00:27:02,000
And so as a result, they'd drop around to the Panther office to find out more about it.

216
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:05,000
And we began to gain recruits.

217
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:08,000
More people to join the party.

218
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:13,000
That was building up to the organization where people coming in.

219
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:32,000
And, you know, like I said, the attitude of many young people coming in was that was the emphasis on the Black Panther Party that we were confront cops and be ready to deal with shootouts and so forth.

220
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:39,000
But when they come in, we'd say, no, we're going to have a political education class.

221
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:42,000
So it's on set tonight.

222
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:49,000
If we hadn't scheduled one, give us a phone number and we'll call you and tell you when we're going to hold it.

223
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:54,000
And we began to teach them revolutionary principles.

224
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:59,000
And more about what we were about.

225
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:05,000
And, you know, it went from there.

226
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:11,000
We weren't in the business of getting anybody killed at that point.

227
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:17,000
But at the same time, we were determined to defend ourselves no matter what.

228
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:24,000
And we were determined to get any of our members arrested.

229
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:33,000
If they went to jail, we were going to do everything we could to get them out as quickly as possible.

230
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:39,000
And so, of course, that pissed the authorities off too.

231
00:28:39,000 --> 00:29:00,000
You know, if you're not creating animosity or hate, then you're not doing very much against the system of the people that propagate or the repressant.

232
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:07,000
So for you personally, I mean, alluded to this some and he talked about the incident at the nightclub.

233
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:12,000
But for you personally, what was driving? What did you want to change?

234
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:15,000
What was it on the meeting?

235
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:18,000
Everything.

236
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:47,000
I taught, you know, I learned a lot from Bobby and stuff in terms of dealing with the yields of the community, you know, like the Denzil Dowell incident in Richmond, where people, I would say, taken notice of the Black Panther Party.

237
00:29:48,000 --> 00:30:05,000
His family, Denzil Dowell's family wasn't getting any answers from the authorities and they were told that they were justified in shooting his kid in the back as he ran and tried to climb a fence.

238
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:14,000
And his mother knew that and told us that he couldn't possibly jump a fence because he had some injury.

239
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:17,000
And so we exposed that as a lie.

240
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:29,000
And we had a demonstration in front of the Richmond Courta House to protest that.

241
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:38,000
At the same time, we developed, we talked about creating our own news media.

242
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:53,000
And this one of the first things we did, we remember grab the sheet off, explaining what happened to Denzil Dowell and the lies that his family was told and so forth.

243
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:59,000
And we took that in the Richmond community and we give it out.

244
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:03,000
And we asked people to come to a rally.

245
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:16,000
And you know, we did that and we asked them if you got a quarter or a dime or something going to donate so that we can continue to produce information like this.

246
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:22,000
And if not, if there was any way, we'd give it to you anyway.

247
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:29,000
And so that was one of the first organized rallies that we had.

248
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:36,000
And by the way, we went, we were armed when we went to that rally.

249
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:44,000
And of course, due to the attention of the police and all that.

250
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:51,000
But you know, it was part of the growing process.

251
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:57,000
I think it's like we just get a little drag in.

252
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:00,000
Thanks.

253
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:09,000
Thank you.

254
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:18,000
Okay.

255
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:20,000
And you said you were armed at that rally.

256
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:28,000
So I wanted to ask you if you could tell me just a little bit about the symbolic power of that of the guy.

257
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:33,000
The symbolic power is that the people in the community saw that.

258
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:45,000
And they saw that, you know, we weren't rushed to put upon by the authority because we were ready to defend ourselves.

259
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:52,000
And it essenceed to defend the community if necessary.

260
00:32:52,000 --> 00:33:02,000
So we had a demonstrated determination to do that and the people saw that.

261
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:08,000
And so that once again drew people to us.

262
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:16,000
So we began to get more requests for support or whatever, you know.

263
00:33:16,000 --> 00:33:31,000
And you know, whenever we were call our alley, bunches and bunches of people would show up without, you know, without fear and with enthusiasm.

264
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:43,000
And we were willing to help us and whatever endeavor we were getting into.

265
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:48,000
You know, like donations for this, that and the other.

266
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:59,000
We needed an office when we had to pay rent for an office to have a focus in the community where people could relate to.

267
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:06,000
Rather than, you know, just a roaming group of young men with guns.

268
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:22,000
So, you know, and I have a place for people to come if they wanted to join, to come and give us a small donation.

269
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:32,000
So, what have you? So we were in the community. We were visible in the community.

270
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:38,000
So, you know, it kind of started there, you know.

271
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:46,000
And that first mimeograph sheet that you had at that rally was at the birth of the Panther News Paper?

272
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:56,000
Yeah. Yeah. Because, you know, Bob and Seal have said something when we had their alley, said, we need our own organ.

273
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:00,000
We need our own news facilities.

274
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:14,000
So, we come up with the thing we were going to mimeograph and I did the text to it.

275
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:19,000
And Bobby Seale did the graphics with the Panther on it" and all of that.

276
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:29,000
And, you know, we gave that out and that was really the beginning of our news outlet.

277
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:33,000
And you were over the newspaper from the beginning of that?

278
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:44,000
Yeah. Yeah. Somehow, we were, you know, all young and feeling our way as I said.

279
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:59,000
I guess as I, you know, I have a little bit of things. I've written a little, little corpse for different little radical publications in the community.

280
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:09,000
And, Bob and Seal said, well, you know, it can be our first editor.

281
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:25,000
You know, it can be the editor of the paper and, you know, we're going to do some progressive moves and develop this thing.

282
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:45,000
And, you know, you can be the editor. And I would say, well, I don't know much about being an editor, but that fierce determination to do whatever was necessary.

283
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:55,000
And, you know, I'll do it. You know, so it started down.

284
00:36:55,000 --> 00:37:05,000
The people write articles and I would read them and do whatever changes ended up saw.

285
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:12,000
I determined that it would be more readable and so forth when we printed it.

286
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:22,000
So it kind of started there, you know. And I said, well, okay. I do whatever was necessary.

287
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:40,000
And, you know, eventually Eldridge Cleaver got out of prison and he was best-selling author with his book, Soul on Ice.

288
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:46,000
And so we're going to make Eldridge Cleaver the editor perhaps a fine, you know.

289
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:56,000
And you'll be a minister of information and you'll be the deputy minister of information. Whatever.

290
00:37:56,000 --> 00:38:02,000
So you'd have the minister title after that point of history of information, yeah.

291
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:05,000
And did that mean giving speeches as well or things like that?

292
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:26,000
No, that came later. It just was dealing with, you know, putting out information, public information to the form of pamphlets or whatever.

293
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:40,000
And we needed a steady stream of information going out. So our rights of our people, our rights of our people and other people.

294
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:52,000
And, you know, we did what we thought was right to put out some cohesive information to the community.

295
00:38:52,000 --> 00:39:04,000
And, but, you know, I never gave too much importance to a title, because it's just wanted to do the work.

296
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:13,000
I just wanted to make, you know, do some stick of fucking fork in the system.

297
00:39:13,000 --> 00:39:25,000
You know, when some of the speeches came later as, you know, more of the main speakers went to jail.

298
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:34,000
And all of that, other people had to step up. And I never considered myself a public speaker or anything.

299
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:49,000
But once again, that old, hard-knows determination said, I was going to do whatever hell it took to advance this vehicle we got going.

300
00:39:49,000 --> 00:39:57,000
So I took a shot at it and turned that all right.

301
00:39:57,000 --> 00:40:09,000
So I keep doing it, keep doing it the more you do it, the more coherent I guess I would.

302
00:40:09,000 --> 00:40:16,000
But that's the way I started.

303
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:21,000
Okay, we'll back.

304
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:30,000
So just before we leave the newspaper, how important you think that paper was to the party, both in terms of keeping money coming in, but putting the message out.

305
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:45,000
Yeah, it was, you know, vital. It was very important. It was vital because we were combating the Oakland Tribune and all the negative shit that they put out about us.

306
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:54,000
And the San Francisco Chronicle, because they were just printed everything negative that they could.

307
00:40:54,000 --> 00:41:02,000
And so, you know, we knew people in the community about those papers and stuff.

308
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:15,000
We said, well, you know, we got to put out things that were the truth when some incident goes down or some issues in the community.

309
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:21,000
We're going to tell the truth about it. And we're going to put it out to the community.

310
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:41,000
And it was very necessary, you know, and as a party grew across the country and our chapters and stuff begin to develop.

311
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:55,000
So we would have, we would require that our chapters and branches send us information about incidents in their community that was concerned in their community and also pictures.

312
00:41:55,000 --> 00:42:09,000
And so they would send that stuff in to Central Headquarters and Oakland. And I would look at it and I would, you know, I read it and edit it and make changes or whatever.

313
00:42:09,000 --> 00:42:16,000
And then we would print it in the newspaper and then we would distribute that newspaper back out across the country.

314
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:24,000
So the people in the community could look at it and see something about what's happening to them in it.

315
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:33,000
And so that's what made it more popular. And so we began to get, you know, demand weekly.

316
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:44,000
And it also brought in revenue. You know, a lot of, not in a lot of many because we would sell a paper for 25 cents.

317
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:58,000
And the party members who didn't have any income go out and sell that paper. They make 15 cents off of it and 10 cents will go into reproduction of the paper.

318
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:08,000
And it helped fund, you know, activity to the party. So, you know, it was kind of way that that worked.

319
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:11,000
And they kept people, kept your party members going.

320
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:18,000
Yeah. And then people, you know, we'd go throughout the community and I'm sure it happened all across the country.

321
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:28,000
We were being the beauty shops, barbershops, restaurants, wherever and told over here, you know, you should read this paper.

322
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:35,000
And if you don't have a quarter, we're going to give it to you. You know, here, you need to read this.

323
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:42,000
And so people began to expect that paper every week. They look for us.

324
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:51,000
And, you know, that's how it developed. Over 250,000 copies printed every week.

325
00:43:51,000 --> 00:44:03,000
And until a lot of work at the party members would spend 24 hours a day putting it together until we got it out and took it to press.

326
00:44:03,000 --> 00:44:13,000
So, you know, it was definitely vital part of the party's program.

327
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:18,000
And were you involved in going and laying it out and not getting it printed and that kind of thing?

328
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:23,000
Yeah. Once again, it was a learning process for me because I never laid out a paper.

329
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:42,000
We had people that had done it before. Some people, very instrumental like Emory Douglas, who knew how to lay out and definitely produced the artwork for that paper.

330
00:44:42,000 --> 00:44:51,000
So people loved that artwork that he had. Something different every week. Something different and relevant.

331
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:56,000
So they could look at it and say, you know, I can relate to this.

332
00:44:56,000 --> 00:45:06,000
And so, you know, we learned and many, many, many party members who at skills contributed.

333
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:16,000
They knew they'd come in and they'd stay up all night and necessarily laying out that paper, you know, getting it right.

334
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:30,000
And we had trouble getting someone printed because the system told people don't print that paper.

335
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:37,000
They have comments, anti-American comments, whatever they told people.

336
00:45:37,000 --> 00:45:43,000
So we had a hard time finding somebody to print for a while.

337
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:54,000
And I went up to Berkeley and talked with Max Scherr, with his name, who ran Max Scherr.

338
00:45:54,000 --> 00:46:01,000
And told him that we were having problems getting our paper printed.

339
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:07,000
And he said, well, we print our paper on some days of the week.

340
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:14,000
So after that, bring yourself up here and you can print it here. You can get it done.

341
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:20,000
So that was a revolutionary step before we were concerned.

342
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:25,000
And this was a little hippie guy in the community.

343
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:41,000
And that was, you know, not only helped us get our paper done, but it also provided a core listen and a solidarity with other groups of people.

344
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:50,000
You know, because we didn't have any foe about him being a hippie or whatever, you know, because he was a progressive guy.

345
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:55,000
And letting us deal with getting our paper out.

346
00:46:55,000 --> 00:47:06,000
And pretty soon, some of the big printers got wind of how much money was in it and how much we were making.

347
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:15,000
So they opened up and let us do it. They didn't like it because the FBI told not to do it.

348
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:24,000
So they knew that we would get on them and print some negative shit about them if they didn't.

349
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:34,000
So rather than fight that bad publicity and get punched on by the government, they would allow us to do it because it was our,

350
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:37,000
I don't know, fifth amendment right or whatever.

351
00:47:37,000 --> 00:47:46,000
But, you know, they would tell if people don't go and help them with anything, you know.

352
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:53,000
And we would be in their office laying out our paper.

353
00:47:53,000 --> 00:47:57,000
But then we had people who wanted to see what we were coming from.

354
00:47:57,000 --> 00:48:04,000
And, you know, a guy would come by and look at the desk.

355
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:11,000
We were working on an article and say, well, he wouldn't let his boss see him do it.

356
00:48:11,000 --> 00:48:14,000
But he said, want to put that down there.

357
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:16,000
Look better.

358
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:22,000
And, you know, so that was progressive, you know.

359
00:48:22,000 --> 00:48:31,000
And so eventually we began to loosen that up and was able to mass produce our paper around.

360
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:51,000
And we had massive distribution and, you know, we had the fact that the government, because the government told the airlines that they should double charge those to do whatever to make it hard for us to ship our paper.

361
00:48:51,000 --> 00:48:58,000
So it was always some, you know, hardship.

362
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:01,000
But we overcome it.

363
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:05,000
We were determined to go around it and stuff.

364
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:12,000
And we were able to get that paper to people on a weekly basis.

365
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:20,000
And it began to not only grow nationally, but we began to get people.

366
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:28,000
From Asia, from Japan, from the African nations, one of that paper.

367
00:49:28,000 --> 00:49:34,000
And so our distribution was really broad.

368
00:49:34,000 --> 00:49:44,000
And, you know, right today, I think if you were found one somewhere, it would cost you over $100.

369
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:47,000
But, here.

370
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:49,000
Our friend Bill Hicks got a collection.

371
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:50,000
Oh, yeah.

372
00:49:50,000 --> 00:49:51,000
Very collection.

373
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:58,000
Yeah.

374
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:05,000
You mentioned early on working on the, I just wanted to follow up on this, working on the 10 point program in Richard Aoki Ioke.

375
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:07,000
What happened to him?

376
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:25,000
He went, well, at the beginning, he, as we began to develop the organization and began to build solidarity with various groups.

377
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:48,000
We, you know, began to see we had a large Asian community in Oakland, large Filipino community, as well as the Mexican Americans and Latino community.

378
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:54,000
So we, things began to really develop.

379
00:50:54,000 --> 00:51:00,000
We've told Richard Aoki why don't you organize the Asian community.

380
00:51:00,000 --> 00:51:10,000
So he began to go up to Berkeley and get involved with the Red Guard Party, I believe, with the organization up there.

381
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:16,000
And he did, you know, a great job in organizing.

382
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:20,000
He would report back to us what was going on and stuff.

383
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:28,000
So that's where, you know, he spent most of his energy as well.

384
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:33,000
We wanted him where we needed him.

385
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:50,000
And so, you know, we had, of course, Puerto Rican community, we've been built a solid area with the young lords and, you know, the American Indian Movement.

386
00:51:50,000 --> 00:52:00,000
And he did a great coalition of American oppressed people.

387
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:14,000
And of course, it raised the anger of the FBI and the established politicians.

388
00:52:14,000 --> 00:52:23,000
But it had to be done, you know.

389
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:39,000
And Richard Aoki, he was, you know, an ally to the end, you know, I could be somewhere and somebody asked me, you know,

390
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:52,000
can you get somebody from the party or the exporter member to come down and participate in this and the other.

391
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:55,000
And I pick up the phone and call Richard Aoki.

392
00:52:55,000 --> 00:53:06,000
And for me, he would always participate and comply, you know, right up until his health store fell.

393
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:15,000
And we were friends, we participated in, you know, different rallies and gathering and so forth.

394
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:34,000
And, in fact, when he knew that he was not going to make it in, only he sent me, he gave me an immediate way, he gave me a big pack of slides.

395
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:38,000
So different things and so forth.

396
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:49,000
But he was a great member, a great ally and a great guy.

397
00:53:49,000 --> 00:53:51,000
I love Richard Aoki.

398
00:53:51,000 --> 00:54:02,000
He was a great writer here a few years ago, wrote something negative, called him FBI and form something.

399
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:07,000
I took, the guy that's trying to fill books.

400
00:54:07,000 --> 00:54:15,000
But anyway, I took a show with that and I wrote a blister and critique of it.

401
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:25,000
And he finally decided he wasn't going to have any benefit from that, so he dropped it.

402
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:30,000
Rolls and felt with his name.

403
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:39,000
There's something you're a teacher.

404
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:49,000
Yeah, I'm getting there.

405
00:54:49,000 --> 00:54:53,000
So, how many more are back?

406
00:54:53,000 --> 00:54:57,000
We'll pick up again.

407
00:54:57,000 --> 00:55:11,000
So, when you were as editor of the paper and then Eldridge came in, so what did you to move on to focus on at that point, your own journey in the party?

408
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:18,000
And I had a brilliant thing to do.

409
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:30,000
We had other people stepping in because Eldridge, he was right off from down in, but he became a popular spokesman.

410
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:36,000
And so, he was always doing this thing.

411
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:49,000
And so, I had people come in and take responsibility for the paper I had other things to do.

412
00:55:49,000 --> 00:56:07,000
Because as many members started to get busing across the country and going to jail and everything, and I was selected if you will to go and deal with that.

413
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:29,000
And I began to cross the country going to different penitentiaries and jails to see about party members, to see what their needs, if they had any needs, and also see what the legal situation was.

414
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:43,000
And see how I could help with their legal defense, talk to lawyers and help lawyers and with things that they needed.

415
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:59,000
And also talk to people in the particular community, whether these people were in jail, and begin to try to organize defense committees in the community to deal with that person out of jail.

416
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:11,000
So I was quite busy with that for a long, long time.

417
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:25,000
My job for a long time, and I go from Denver to New Orleans, where we had people locked up and stuff.

418
00:57:25,000 --> 00:57:35,000
And some of the biggest issues came up, and they were framing Bobby Seale and Ericka Huggins and all those people in New Haven.

419
00:57:35,000 --> 00:57:43,000
I had to pick up and move to New Haven and work on those issues.

420
00:57:43,000 --> 00:57:59,000
And so, you know, a lot of people didn't, wasn't public knowledge what I did, you know, and news paper written and all that stuff.

421
00:57:59,000 --> 00:58:19,000
And it was fine with me, because I had my hands full, dodging the authorities and sad, stiff and traps that they might be setting for me, and moving and doing what I needed to do.

422
00:58:19,000 --> 00:58:32,000
Can I ask a little bit more about that, about that particular period, when the party was really being targeted, and there was a lot of pressure on you, and you said you had people incarcerated, obviously.

423
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:37,000
So how are people dealing, how are you dealing with all of that?

424
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:52,000
Well, I like to think that I relied a great deal on people in the community, you know, because we had friends and all, and different places.

425
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:59,000
A lot of friends, they were, you know, public knowledge or anything like that.

426
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:08,000
We had people that would, you know, contribute money for bail and things of this nature.

427
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:34,000
And when I was in a community, and they needed more community support, I would engineer survival programs, if you would, help with free breakfast programs, help them set up a free clothing program in that community, and get people to contribute to those things.

428
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:52,000
And as a result, it began to get community support behind these incarcerated party members to try to get them out of jail and get them through the court system and get them free.

429
00:59:52,000 --> 00:59:58,000
So it didn't tell a lot of different things, you know.

430
00:59:58,000 --> 01:00:06,000
Was that high stress times for you? Just trying to stay one step ahead of the feds and all that.

431
01:00:06,000 --> 01:00:22,000
Of course, but I didn't bother about that, because I, in doing what I did, I always sat step to obvious bullshit that would get you busted.

432
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:33,000
And then, you know, leave myself open to any of the chats that they laid, you know.

433
01:00:33,000 --> 01:00:50,000
For instance, a new hearing, I got very little sleep because in the house, I would stay at, they would telephone all night long, which shit, like I've got a cash or weapons.

434
01:00:50,000 --> 01:00:58,000
I got a dime from dynamite and all this shit, and I never responded to it, it was hanging up to telephone.

435
01:00:58,000 --> 01:01:09,000
Because it was all in trapment, you know. And, you know, we began to know these things, and you just don't deal with them, you know.

436
01:01:09,000 --> 01:01:15,000
And so, you know, I know people call and pretending to offer these things, so they're already in those places.

437
01:01:15,000 --> 01:01:23,000
And, you know, I knew, they asked me, who was people, you know. I knew that.

438
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:32,000
So, I didn't accommodate any of it, you know.

439
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:45,000
You know, I just hang up the phone, leave it out the hood, get a couple hours sleep, and get up and start strategizing on what needed to be done.

440
01:01:45,000 --> 01:02:00,000
You know, who I needed to see, who I needed to talk to, to matter of endless meeting with people, to explain crap, and explain what our programs were,

441
01:02:00,000 --> 01:02:09,000
and what is shit supported, and stuff like that, you know. You just had to keep going.

442
01:02:09,000 --> 01:02:16,000
So, since you, I wanted to ask you this question, since you were traveling around the country in this way,

443
01:02:16,000 --> 01:02:34,000
are there certain, were there certain chapters of the party or certain places that most people don't know about that are, that are sort of dear to you or are interested that you'd like people to know about places where the Panther Party existed and did good work?

444
01:02:34,000 --> 01:02:50,000
Well, I know there are a lot of different situations, you know, like down in Memphis, there was a group of young college kids that called themselves invaders.

445
01:02:50,000 --> 01:02:58,000
I think they picked it up from some TV program or something, but they were trying to do something in the community, you know.

446
01:02:58,000 --> 01:03:17,000
And so, you know, they heard about us and knew about us, and we got with them and sort of explained our programs to them, and things that suggested things that they should be doing and everything.

447
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:28,000
And they got with that program, and we eventually inducted them into it, and instead of the innovative, they became a chapter of the Black Panther Party.

448
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:45,000
So, it was a matter of communicating with people, you know, and giving little advice where needed or whatever, and learning what their ambitions were, what they contribute.

449
01:03:45,000 --> 01:03:57,000
And making suggestions and so on, you know. So, you know, building an Augusta College solidarity, you know.

450
01:03:57,000 --> 01:04:12,000
And communicating with, I'm going to say to the Latino community who were doing things in their community, and we forward solidarity with them, you know.

451
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:26,000
Well, as an anti-war moment, and all that, just a matter of becoming involved with anything that was oppressing people, you know.

452
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:33,000
And they're damn about the consequences of care, you know. Go to jail.

453
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:48,000
So, you go to jail and you use that equipment tool, because every time that I went to jail, I'm sitting on a bunk talking to people about the Black Panther Party, you know.

454
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:53,000
And explaining reasons, political reasons why they're sitting in jail.

455
01:04:53,000 --> 01:05:03,000
So, when they got out of jail, they'd come around to the Black Panther Party office. And, you know, so you're never quit.

456
01:05:03,000 --> 01:05:17,000
You know, we had people in prison, George Jackson, who got murdered because he was organizer of the prison system, Nationwide.

457
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:30,000
You know, still consider the hero by incarcerated prison around the country.

458
01:05:30,000 --> 01:05:38,000
And so, we just never stopped. And that's why they wound up.

459
01:05:38,000 --> 01:05:52,000
They couldn't brim us out. They couldn't get people to not support us and all that. So, it came right down to outright assassination and killings, to wipe us out, you know.

460
01:05:52,000 --> 01:06:09,000
It was a whole campaign, but that was why, because we had die-hard determination that we were going to do whatever it took to free our community and deal with the problems of oppression.

461
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:19,000
You know, so, you know, it was quite a phenomenon.

462
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:30,000
You know, and some of the things that people don't know about it, and talk about it, it's all these young people that come to the party.

463
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:49,000
Some of them came with heavy issues from things that happened in their lives or didn't happen in their lives. And the Black Panther Party changed their perspective on things.

464
01:06:49,000 --> 01:07:11,000
We changed them. We had people come in that had been to jail, been to prison. They had major issues. And we politically educated them and showed them how and why these things were happening. And as a result, they joined the party and the party to philosophy.

465
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:22,000
And some of them went to prison and stayed in there 40 years. And they never lost that perspective about what the party was all about.

466
01:07:22,000 --> 01:07:40,000
And, you know, we took young people who were didn't have anything to do but hang out and get in the trouble. And we recruited them and taught them how to cook breakfast for children.

467
01:07:40,000 --> 01:07:56,000
They wanted a gun to go out and kill somebody which said, no, no, no, no, no. You're coming in, you're going in there, some sisters in the kitchen and learn how to cook, get some eggs and get up and go and serve breakfast with the school children.

468
01:07:56,000 --> 01:08:10,000
You go out when you're doing the middle of the day, you got nothing to do, you go out and try to get donations for these programs. Try to get people to donate clothing for our clothing program.

469
01:08:10,000 --> 01:08:26,000
We gave them something to do and we changed their attitude and people don't realize that some of these kids, you know, we prevented them from crawling through their windows.

470
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:45,000
Now, how's it been taking their shit and instead of doing that, they had some progressive work to do. Some things to benefit the community. So people don't, you know, don't really have to call a bunch of tubs and crooks and just send that to the other.

471
01:08:45,000 --> 01:08:54,000
But we changed people's attitude. We changed their agenda in light.

472
01:08:54,000 --> 01:09:10,000
A lot of people had a lot of reasons to be angry. Yeah. They would come with this anger. Yeah. So we changed all out of that. We channeled that into something beneficial to the community.

473
01:09:10,000 --> 01:09:29,000
And I think that was a major achievement and people don't realize that because we did not fill up the prisons with dog addicts and criminals. We didn't do that.

474
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:43,000
You know, we saved a lot of them from that fate by giving them something to do, giving them a place to live, providing food for them.

475
01:09:43,000 --> 01:10:10,000
And when they pay off for doing that, was them going out into the community and doing stuff for people, you know, telling me, you know, you're living in a community, go down the street and see a lady grass and you cut it.

476
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:24,000
And don't take a dime for it. Don't take anything for it. Because, tell them, you see something come up and an issue come up where the Black Panther Party is supporting some program, go vote for it.

477
01:10:24,000 --> 01:10:36,000
That would be payment enough for us. So as a result, people begin to understand what we're about and at the same time,

478
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:43,000
it calls the authorities to hate us more. You know.

479
01:10:43,000 --> 01:10:48,000
So why were you so threatening to them, do you say, to the powers of B?

480
01:10:48,000 --> 01:11:03,000
Because we've, first of all, exposed them. We can see 250,000 children free food every single day of the schools and session. Why can't the government do anything about it?

481
01:11:03,000 --> 01:11:29,000
Well, if we can test people for sick of celinemia, which is a disease that they pretty much ignored. If we can establish free health clinics, well, people could go and be tested and engage in preventative medical care.

482
01:11:29,000 --> 01:11:51,000
Why can't the government do it? Things like that, you know, is what calls them the haters. So, you know, just on and on all these survival programs, free education.

483
01:11:51,000 --> 01:12:10,000
We started liberation school when people threw up their hands because their kids, they say, couldn't be educated and going to put out on the street and be candidate for going to jail or prison.

484
01:12:10,000 --> 01:12:24,000
We had liberation school, we'd get them young and get them in and taught them relevant education, something that dealt with their reality and they were teaching them to read and stuff like that.

485
01:12:24,000 --> 01:12:43,000
And at the same time, recruiting people who had the skills to teach, who were fed up with the bureaucracy of the educational system, who would come in and help us with the liberation school of the teachers' kids.

486
01:12:43,000 --> 01:13:01,000
And we had some great successes, we got some kids running around now, who were very appreciative that they went to the Panther School. And so stuff like that, government, this government was very unsililized about it.

487
01:13:01,000 --> 01:13:07,000
And the party was that you answered a call to or an invitation to come to Japan.

488
01:13:07,000 --> 01:13:13,000
Yeah. Can you tell us a little bit about how that arose and what that turned out?

489
01:13:13,000 --> 01:13:29,000
During that period, there were massive student rebellions and protests, and along with the anti-war movement and so forth.

490
01:13:29,000 --> 01:13:43,000
We had some Japanese students who got wind of the party and what we were about and they wanted someone to come to Japan, you know, and they were very persistent.

491
01:13:43,000 --> 01:13:56,000
And kept after us, finally the leadership said, I'm a big man, you're going and take Roberta with you.

492
01:13:56,000 --> 01:14:04,000
So we took that long flight to Japan. And that's Roberta Alexander that you're going to.

493
01:14:04,000 --> 01:14:14,000
Yeah. Yeah. And we got there and not speaking the language or anything.

494
01:14:14,000 --> 01:14:35,000
And we hooked up with our name, you're speaking person that was living in Japan, who helped us a lot. But more than that, these people wanted us to speak to the student by the student protestors.

495
01:14:35,000 --> 01:14:52,000
And I haven't seen so many people at a rally. And, you know, like I said, it was anti-war rally, railing against the enemy's war.

496
01:14:52,000 --> 01:15:09,000
And, excuse me, and students over there, they had, I guess, a repressive system where, you know, the younger people were trying to break out of that.

497
01:15:09,000 --> 01:15:29,000
And they were rebelling against, you know, their historical culture where you couldn't, you know, talk back to Eldridge Cleaver and, you know, they had no say".

498
01:15:29,000 --> 01:15:50,000
And so they were breaking out the student for clothing down universities all over the place. And so we were, you know, introduced to some of the, I guess, more radical organizations and people.

499
01:15:50,000 --> 01:16:17,000
And they, you know, had us go around to different provinces and, you know, meet people and attend these big gatherings and like that. And so, you know, Roberta and I, you know, we hung in there all at the same time being followed by,

500
01:16:17,000 --> 01:16:33,000
I guess, Japanese version of the FBI, they were under the FBI's instructions to follow and, you know, keep tabs on us, I guess, you know.

501
01:16:33,000 --> 01:16:56,000
And we know that they weren't slick as the American, you know, we'd be walking down the street and they'd be following us and they were, let's make a quick stop, turn around, stop, turn around. And these guys, I like they weren't following us. It was comical, you know.

502
01:16:56,000 --> 01:17:19,000
But we had some fun with that. And, you know, and they followed us everywhere. And we went to a lot of different cities, you know. And, and it was, you know, an experience.

503
01:17:19,000 --> 01:17:40,000
But we hooked up with Japanese film maker and they were to get his name Shinsuke Ogawa. He had a film company. He made, I guess, documentaries or whatever, you know. And he sponsored us going to different places.

504
01:17:40,000 --> 01:18:07,000
And, you know, and it was an experience. I know, I guess we spent a month there on war. And, you know, it was something else. And of course, we were in all papers, you know.

505
01:18:07,000 --> 01:18:21,000
And I do what they said. We're all over the place. And we were treated quite well. You know.

506
01:18:21,000 --> 01:18:38,000
So, when time comes to leave, the World War II got to come home. But they told me you're going directly to sleep after that. So, I didn't.

507
01:18:38,000 --> 01:18:55,000
They wanted me to go there and work with support committees that had developed. We had people that developed support committees in Denmark and Sweden.

508
01:18:55,000 --> 01:19:24,000
And so, I went there and, you know, of course, they visited Paris and went into Germany and spoke with a lot of GIs that were serving there who had our paper and who knew about us and wanted to, you know, hear about what was going on.

509
01:19:25,000 --> 01:19:49,000
And the country and wanted to know about, you know, the party and stuff like that. So, you know, we went to one base. I forget where it was. But anyway, in the city and the base commander, the zombie base knew we were coming.

510
01:19:49,000 --> 01:20:05,000
And he blacked out the base, we were getting there in the evening at night. And the GIs had, you know, decided that they were going to host us with something.

511
01:20:05,000 --> 01:20:25,000
And the base commander cut out all the power. No lights at all. So, I hear this, as we were standing out on the street talking around a corner, he had come to the formation of GIs.

512
01:20:25,000 --> 01:20:41,000
And, you know, they say, well, the base commander heard you were coming and he called the blackout. So, if you don't mind, coming will go to this local village.

513
01:20:41,000 --> 01:21:07,000
And, you know, we can sit down and talk because, you know, we want to talk to you. And so, we did that. And we went and talked most of the night. And they wanted to know who was going on in America. And what the black Panther Party was all about, you know, they got our paper and knew, you know, something about it.

514
01:21:07,000 --> 01:21:29,000
And so, they wanted to know more. So, that was a really good experience, you know, to sit down and of course, we talked about, you know, our feelings about the war. And, you know, why should rebel against sitting, sitting, participating and so on.

515
01:21:29,000 --> 01:21:35,000
So, that was, how are they feeling about things?

516
01:21:35,000 --> 01:21:53,000
Oh, they were, you know, they were in accordance with what they had picked up from the black Panther Party. You know, matter of fact, they, you know, were forming some kind of organization of their own, you know.

517
01:21:53,000 --> 01:22:10,000
In relation to that, and [which/that] didn't sit well with their command didn't sit well with their command and officer and so forth. But it was, you know, a great thing to see so far from home.

518
01:22:10,000 --> 01:22:28,000
You know, and, you know, black G.I. had no good in the fight in the re-enemy. So, it was good to talk to them.

519
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:34,000
So, you served at this kind of an international ambassador for a while and then you headed back home?

520
01:22:34,000 --> 01:22:48,000
Yeah, yeah. And I worked with those support committees and they said speaking engagements all over the place for schools and colleges and so forth.

521
01:22:48,000 --> 01:23:08,000
So, you know, I spoke a lot to the meetings of exchange and the money wasn't that great, but, you know, they financed our travel and stuff while we were in there, area and so forth.

522
01:23:08,000 --> 01:23:23,000
We stayed pretty busy going around to these colleges and universities and so forth and in Sweden and Denmark.

523
01:23:23,000 --> 01:23:44,000
And I think we went up to Finland, I believe. It kept us pretty busy. And I know at one point, Bobby Seale, they got put in jail in New Haven.

524
01:23:44,000 --> 01:24:01,000
He's been extradited to New Haven or whatever, but anyway, he was under the charge of murder, of Alex Rackley and they sent me a message. You need to come home right away, you know.

525
01:24:01,000 --> 01:24:14,000
You need you once on the paper and also help, you know, organize and do something to save Bobbi or whatever, you know.

526
01:24:14,000 --> 01:24:34,000
So, I was very anxious to get back home and I got wind of that, you know, what the hell, you know. And I came back and I had to move to New Haven and so I did them with all of that.

527
01:24:34,000 --> 01:24:44,000
And were you there during that whole time that he and Ericka Huggins were in prison? Yeah, that was 14 months or 18 months.

528
01:24:45,000 --> 01:24:56,000
And so we, you know, dealt with a lot of people, had a lot of people come in for support, you know.

529
01:24:57,000 --> 01:25:12,000
Daniel Berrigan and Dr. Benjamin Spock and all people like that, we got to come to New Haven and had big rallies. I think I have a picture of some of it up there, maybe I don't know.

530
01:25:12,000 --> 01:25:31,000
But anyway, we had to generate support and on a daily basis and people of New Haven were frightened of that.

531
01:25:32,000 --> 01:25:38,000
And they thought things were going to explode. We said stuff like that for Sky's Olympic.

532
01:25:38,000 --> 01:25:49,000
And they better not happen to Bobbi or New Haven being ashes, rhetoric.

533
01:25:50,000 --> 01:25:55,000
Scared to hell out of them people in New England though.

534
01:25:55,000 --> 01:26:08,000
And so, you know, we had people like Kingman Brewster, yeah, they said, you know, revolutionary, King, Ditto, Fried Trial, up here or whatever.

535
01:26:09,000 --> 01:26:26,000
So, you know, the judges and courts" and Kurtz went through their routine under pressure from the FBI and the local law enforcement who they rule and so on.

536
01:26:27,000 --> 01:26:40,000
And they thought that the best thing they could do was get rid of this clock, get rid of this, get it out of a nice, pristine New Haven community.

537
01:26:40,000 --> 01:26:47,000
Or, for something bad happens and get Yale burned down.

538
01:26:48,000 --> 01:27:08,000
So, I think that had a lot to do with the judges and courts"'s decision to get rid of this case because he didn't want to be responsible for any mayhem that might come about, you know, man.

539
01:27:09,000 --> 01:27:15,000
So, after that, after New Haven, how much longer were you in the party?

540
01:27:15,000 --> 01:27:22,000
Well, after the trial and everything, I was getting rid of it, I've come back to California and come home.

541
01:27:22,000 --> 01:27:29,000
And I got a telephone call and some more crap. Attica Correctional Facility had exploded.

542
01:27:30,000 --> 01:27:43,000
And the inmates had asked for the panthers to come up and negotiate the piece, the settlement or whatever of that.

543
01:27:43,000 --> 01:27:53,000
And they told me Bobby Seale was coming, so don't go nowhere. I'll be coming through.

544
01:27:54,000 --> 01:28:10,000
And we want you to go with him to Attica Correctional Facility. So, we went up to the prison, went through all of that and, you know, talked with attorneys that they were trying to do something.

545
01:28:11,000 --> 01:28:23,000
And the prison warden and those people were hopeful that we would be able to quill it and all of that.

546
01:28:23,000 --> 01:28:29,000
But as a result, Nelson Rockefeller wasn't having it.

547
01:28:30,000 --> 01:28:39,000
And one thing that could have saved that explosion was for him to just show up or say he was going to show up.

548
01:28:39,000 --> 01:28:44,000
And he, I guess he was getting rid of for re-election or something.

549
01:28:44,000 --> 01:28:51,000
And he had a platform of being tough on crime and some crap like that.

550
01:28:52,000 --> 01:28:59,000
And so he refused to come. He refused to talk to the inmates, so make any concessions.

551
01:28:59,000 --> 01:29:06,000
And he, you know, pretty much hung the situation out the track.

552
01:29:06,000 --> 01:29:19,000
And a lot of people lost their lives without, you know, needlessly. Didn't have to happen.

553
01:29:20,000 --> 01:29:33,000
So we were there and I think after we went into the prison and listened to the inmates, the people that were occupying the yard and all of that.

554
01:29:33,000 --> 01:29:47,000
And I think Bobby told them, well, you know, I need to go and confer with you and leadership of the party to see what we can do.

555
01:29:48,000 --> 01:29:53,000
And you were able to go inside the prison during occupation.

556
01:29:53,000 --> 01:30:10,000
And there was kind of a disheartening thing to walk out on the yard, you know, and people were like, hey, big man, you know.

557
01:30:11,000 --> 01:30:17,000
And, you know, a few days later, people were dead, you know.

558
01:30:17,000 --> 01:30:24,000
Just sit there, think of strong heart to deal with.

559
01:30:24,000 --> 01:30:29,000
But anyways, you know, kill all those people.

560
01:30:30,000 --> 01:30:42,000
And to see how pitiful the families of the guards were before, you know, before we went in, we were right there outside the prison.

561
01:30:42,000 --> 01:30:48,000
These people, Megan, please, please do something.

562
01:30:49,000 --> 01:30:53,000
You know, because my loved one is in there, you know.

563
01:30:53,000 --> 01:30:56,000
And then when you go in there, you see these guards.

564
01:30:56,000 --> 01:31:01,000
The prisoners had made the guards change clothes with them, you know.

565
01:31:01,000 --> 01:31:05,000
And they're sitting out there on the yard in front of a fire.

566
01:31:05,000 --> 01:31:12,000
And they're looking, you know, defeated and scared.

567
01:31:13,000 --> 01:31:19,000
And, you know, you look at that sit and you know, you kind of take that away with you.

568
01:31:19,000 --> 01:31:29,000
And then the next day, I was going to throw a game of the order to take back the prison.

569
01:31:29,000 --> 01:31:39,000
And they just opened the kill of people like shooting chickens in a barrel or something, you know.

570
01:31:40,000 --> 01:31:46,000
That's all kind of shit, man.

571
01:31:55,000 --> 01:32:03,000
And there's proven later on that the guards didn't kill anybody.

572
01:32:04,000 --> 01:32:10,000
And all these things that were propagated and put in the newspaper are.

573
01:32:18,000 --> 01:32:19,000
So, anyway.

574
01:32:19,000 --> 01:32:22,000
So you were dealing with a lot of stuff.

575
01:32:22,000 --> 01:32:23,000
Yeah.

576
01:32:28,000 --> 01:32:31,000
Where it would come up is.

577
01:32:34,000 --> 01:32:37,000
Couldn't have ordered you to just jump with it, you know.

578
01:32:37,000 --> 01:32:45,000
Trying to keep your sanity and keep your goal and your mind.

579
01:32:45,000 --> 01:32:49,000
What you wanted to do.

580
01:32:49,000 --> 01:32:52,000
What you needed to do.

581
01:32:52,000 --> 01:32:54,000
You know.

582
01:32:54,000 --> 01:33:01,000
Is that certain to where you are at that point or you're able to find reserves or start to think about moving on to something else?

583
01:33:02,000 --> 01:33:06,000
You know, that was always something.

584
01:33:06,000 --> 01:33:07,000
69.

585
01:33:10,000 --> 01:33:19,000
You never knew what to expect and you know, you get the call and go here and say, and the other.

586
01:33:20,000 --> 01:33:33,000
You just, I don't know, something in my personality just made me deal with it and get through it.

587
01:33:33,000 --> 01:33:36,000
You know, there was a state of things.

588
01:33:36,000 --> 01:33:41,000
I get a call from the, you know, the uprising of COINTELPRO.

589
01:33:41,000 --> 01:33:43,000
We didn't know what it was called at that time.

590
01:33:44,000 --> 01:33:49,000
But anyway, I get a call from New Haven, the good out in New York.

591
01:33:49,000 --> 01:33:52,000
And since Sam Napier, they pure home.

592
01:33:52,000 --> 01:33:57,000
And they didn't say what the hell it was about.

593
01:33:57,000 --> 01:34:01,000
You know, since Sam Napier home, we talked about it.

594
01:34:01,000 --> 01:34:07,000
And then they finally broke down and told me Sam Napier's been killed.

595
01:34:08,000 --> 01:34:10,000
I don't know what Sam Napier, I don't know what to kill.

596
01:34:10,000 --> 01:34:13,000
I know what Sam Napier's been with distribution.

597
01:34:13,000 --> 01:34:16,000
New is favorite distribution manager for.

598
01:34:16,000 --> 01:34:21,000
He had nothing to do with any military arm or party or anything.

599
01:34:21,000 --> 01:34:32,000
So I go down there and we go about our office where it happened when he killed him and set the office on fire,

600
01:34:32,000 --> 01:34:36,000
which was a pant and a distribution center.

601
01:34:36,000 --> 01:34:51,000
They set it on fire and someone there took us to a hotel where told us that there were some ladies and a group of children scared to death.

602
01:34:52,000 --> 01:34:55,000
Because this here was the beginning.

603
01:34:55,000 --> 01:35:02,000
I didn't realize how strong this was, but between East Coast, West Coast.

604
01:35:02,000 --> 01:35:05,000
And this is what this shit was all about.

605
01:35:05,000 --> 01:35:15,000
And these ladies had these children didn't know if someone was coming and kill them or what.

606
01:35:16,000 --> 01:35:22,000
And so we went to this hotel where they were held up.

607
01:35:22,000 --> 01:35:33,000
And I told two comrades that we were with them and say, well, you know, first sort of been, you know, Sam Napier is in the morgue.

608
01:35:33,000 --> 01:35:35,000
He's not going anywhere.

609
01:35:35,000 --> 01:35:41,000
The first thing we need to do is find a safe place for these women and these children.

610
01:35:42,000 --> 01:35:48,000
And so we made some calls and found a place where they would take them to.

611
01:35:48,000 --> 01:35:50,000
It would be safe and all of that.

612
01:35:50,000 --> 01:36:01,000
And as soon as we stepped out of that hotel, here's the cops everywhere screaming yelling like they do.

613
01:36:01,000 --> 01:36:06,000
Guns drawn, you know.

614
01:36:07,000 --> 01:36:16,000
And I backed up against the wall and I was able to pull out my gun and drop it behind me.

615
01:36:16,000 --> 01:36:23,000
And they took us to jail.

616
01:36:23,000 --> 01:36:25,000
They didn't take us directly to jail.

617
01:36:25,000 --> 01:36:28,000
They put us in a paddy wagon.

618
01:36:28,000 --> 01:36:32,000
And this was about, I don't know, two or three in the afternoon.

619
01:36:32,000 --> 01:36:52,000
And they drove us around until about 10 or 11 o'clock at night before they took us to jail to, I guess, to hold us until, I don't know, until the lawyer stopped looking for us.

620
01:36:52,000 --> 01:36:55,000
I guess I was. I'm pretty sure it was.

621
01:36:55,000 --> 01:37:00,000
We were out of touch. We couldn't call anybody.

622
01:37:00,000 --> 01:37:06,000
We wanted what the hell was going on.

623
01:37:06,000 --> 01:37:16,000
Finally they took us and booked us into jail and into the Tombs, I guess it was.

624
01:37:16,000 --> 01:37:20,000
And it took us from a local precinct to the Tombs.

625
01:37:20,000 --> 01:37:29,000
And that's where we began our process of getting ready to charge us with something.

626
01:37:29,000 --> 01:37:38,000
But anyway, they had us in jail for a couple of days.

627
01:37:38,000 --> 01:37:57,000
And finally, the attorney finally found out what we were and came and told me, you know, what we had to appear before judge.

628
01:37:57,000 --> 01:38:07,000
And we got a sympathetic assistant, you know, African American young lady.

629
01:38:07,000 --> 01:38:13,000
And she said, well, you sit tight for a day or so.

630
01:38:13,000 --> 01:38:17,000
A judge is going to be on the bench that I can talk to.

631
01:38:17,000 --> 01:38:21,000
And, you know, we can see about what we can do.

632
01:38:21,000 --> 01:38:25,000
And she knew that we were panthers, you know.

633
01:38:25,000 --> 01:38:32,000
And so in the meantime, William Kunstler had located us.

634
01:38:32,000 --> 01:38:39,000
And he came and told me that part of leadership told him to get me out.

635
01:38:39,000 --> 01:38:46,000
And that I would deal with getting my comrades out and take care of that.

636
01:38:46,000 --> 01:38:50,000
So that's what they did.

637
01:38:50,000 --> 01:39:08,000
You know, we finally went to a judge and he said, well, told me, I'm going to dismiss the charges and let you go on the unconditioned, that you leave New York and never come back.

638
01:39:08,000 --> 01:39:11,000
And I say, yeah, all right.

639
01:39:11,000 --> 01:39:17,000
And my other fucking thing, he's just Roy Binging.

640
01:39:17,000 --> 01:39:20,000
You can post me out of town.

641
01:39:20,000 --> 01:39:24,000
So, anyway, I said, okay.

642
01:39:24,000 --> 01:39:33,000
I got went back up to New Haven and started back working, what I was doing, what I was doing.

643
01:39:33,000 --> 01:39:36,000
But anyway, it was some of the never-ending things.

644
01:39:36,000 --> 01:39:44,000
In the time, meantime, I never needed to get to see Sam" Napier, but Pauline and his wife came down.

645
01:39:44,000 --> 01:39:52,000
And she claimed the body and made a range of it to get him back out for you.

646
01:39:52,000 --> 01:39:56,000
Just all kinds of stuff, man.

647
01:39:56,000 --> 01:40:02,000
Unbelievable repression.

648
01:40:02,000 --> 01:40:16,000
And during that period, the East Coast, West Coast thing was escalating due to the press and so on.

649
01:40:16,000 --> 01:40:36,000
And somehow, the New York Panthers thought it was, let's see.

650
01:40:36,000 --> 01:40:50,000
And they thought it was that Sam Napier had been killed by East Coast Panthers.

651
01:40:50,000 --> 01:40:56,000
So Robert Webb, who was actually from the West Coast for working the East Coast,

652
01:40:56,000 --> 01:41:04,000
was shining the head on the streets of New York as supposedly retaliation for Sam Napier.

653
01:41:04,000 --> 01:41:16,000
So then the killing began.

654
01:41:17,000 --> 01:41:31,000
There was sitting tent.

655
01:41:31,000 --> 01:41:49,000
We love Sam Napier. I have a meant to work this horn as him, because he took control of the distribution of that paper early on.

656
01:41:50,000 --> 01:42:00,000
And anytime, I could very Sam Napier, how many papers we got going to New York, and he would write all the exact number.

657
01:42:00,000 --> 01:42:04,000
He would tell me who it sent them money in.

658
01:42:04,000 --> 01:42:15,000
He was just a phenomenal guy that seemed like he came out of nowhere with those skills.

659
01:42:15,000 --> 01:42:26,000
And he had put together a dynamite crew to help him in Skoglade.

660
01:42:27,000 --> 01:42:35,000
And he said, stuff like, circle like to educate, get the papers out.

661
01:42:35,000 --> 01:42:39,000
Yeah, yeah.

662
01:42:39,000 --> 01:42:50,000
Great, great ways to let him.

663
01:42:51,000 --> 01:43:02,000
So after all of this and handling all this, what did you do?

664
01:43:03,000 --> 01:43:11,000
I was able to finally come back from the East Coast.

665
01:43:11,000 --> 01:43:18,000
I pretty much worked out, I guess, out of central headquarters.

666
01:43:19,000 --> 01:43:28,000
And let's begin to work on programs.

667
01:43:29,000 --> 01:43:50,000
And the meantime, I had been selected by the president of Merritt College as an almost-boothed buzzman, they called it.

668
01:43:51,000 --> 01:43:56,000
And I had to work with Mary.

669
01:43:56,000 --> 01:44:11,000
He put me in charge of work study program to be able to run the budget on that, had a budget that I had to work with on that.

670
01:44:12,000 --> 01:44:19,000
I had a lot of opportunities there to benefit the community.

671
01:44:19,000 --> 01:44:39,000
So I knew that out at the center, the center of Edel, they had a system where in order to get out of person, the old, the bulls of parole.

672
01:44:40,000 --> 01:44:46,000
And I said, well, that stinks. How are you going to get a job sitting in jail?

673
01:44:46,000 --> 01:44:56,000
And I talked to Dr. Young Park, who was president, and who had hired me.

674
01:44:57,000 --> 01:45:10,000
And I went to use some of the work study funds to provide education opportunities for some of these prisoners.

675
01:45:10,000 --> 01:45:14,000
And he said, well, you know, all right.

676
01:45:14,000 --> 01:45:24,000
I said, well, you know, I need somebody to help me with the adult authority to get them released.

677
01:45:24,000 --> 01:45:44,000
So he went with me to sit down with the California adult authority, and we put the perspective to them that we would take on people on probation.

678
01:45:45,000 --> 01:46:04,000
We would enter them into the college, and those that didn't have a high school diploma, we would get them into a work study program, and get them on a GED program.

679
01:46:05,000 --> 01:46:20,000
And those that had some high school had finished high school, you know, if they wanted to pursue going to a four year college, we could enter them into a program, and they could work toward that.

680
01:46:20,000 --> 01:46:27,000
And so it was, you know, an awful good refuse.

681
01:46:28,000 --> 01:46:47,000
We set that up, and I had parolees coming to the school and enrolling in classes, and they knew it was pretty much a panther program, as I was in charge of it.

682
01:46:48,000 --> 01:47:01,000
I told me, you know, you got to abide by your education requirements, and you're going to get a stipend every two weeks to help you live.

683
01:47:01,000 --> 01:47:15,000
And we also have an on-campus food program where we got food meal tickets for you to eat twice, breakfast and lunch while you're on campus.

684
01:47:16,000 --> 01:47:37,000
And in the meantime, you pursue your studies, you keep up with your attendance, and if we need you to work to help the library move something or move things around, you're going to help with that.

685
01:47:38,000 --> 01:47:45,000
And that would be about the only type of labor that you have to do, you just maintain a program.

686
01:47:45,000 --> 01:47:52,000
And so that worked pretty well for a while, you know.

687
01:47:53,000 --> 01:48:09,000
And what killed the program was, we had an instructor's name was Felix Poindra.

688
01:48:09,000 --> 01:48:12,000
I think her name was Felix Poindra.

689
01:48:13,000 --> 01:48:26,000
And he was definitely a critic of the party, and he would say things in his classes, critical of the party.

690
01:48:26,000 --> 01:48:40,000
And in the meantime, we had some panthers in those classes, and one day it kind of exploded, and they jumped up and knocked him under the ass in the classroom.

691
01:48:40,000 --> 01:48:57,000
So, you know, that was a assault on a county employee, I guess you call it, so they got the Dr. Park and Dr. Park to me.

692
01:48:57,000 --> 01:49:00,000
I can't save you on this one.

693
01:49:01,000 --> 01:49:07,000
So, you know, that ended the program, but it was quite successful, for quite a while.

694
01:49:07,000 --> 01:49:24,000
You know, so, the other things that, you know, I thought that was beneficial to the people in the community, and it would help these people that

695
01:49:24,000 --> 01:49:35,000
would then deal to come out and contribute a little bit to their families, and have a viable program that took them somewhere.

696
01:49:35,000 --> 01:49:44,000
So, anyway, they did things like that, you know.

697
01:49:44,000 --> 01:49:53,000
They attended endless meetings dealing with endless programs, you know.

698
01:49:53,000 --> 01:50:12,000
I remember having to go to a meeting with all these people in different forms of disability, people, you know, room for wheelchairs and stuff.

699
01:50:12,000 --> 01:50:24,000
And I remember what the hell there was this, and once again something told me, keeping my set in your ears open and you learn something.

700
01:50:24,000 --> 01:50:41,000
And so, these people were protesting, not being able to get the wheelchairs on sidewalks or get them into a federal or county buildings where they had a right to go and stuff.

701
01:50:41,000 --> 01:51:00,000
And we talked and eventually come down to, you know, threatening to go out into the street with these wheelchairs and stop trackers.

702
01:51:00,000 --> 01:51:11,000
So, protest that way. And as a result, we got sidewalk cut so people had ramps.

703
01:51:11,000 --> 01:51:25,000
We got these ramps put on city buildings, and, you know, people don't know that that was Panther involvement.

704
01:51:25,000 --> 01:51:43,000
But, just things like that, helping people organize rent strikes where they had pain on their walls and their housing, lead-based paint that make kids sick and stuff like that.

705
01:51:43,000 --> 01:51:56,000
We had to organize rent strikes until landlord, if they didn't repaint these places and get rid of that stuff, that they wouldn't even get paid.

706
01:51:57,000 --> 01:52:12,000
And so, you know, rent strikes caused some redevelopment there, and they painted, they complied with it.

707
01:52:12,000 --> 01:52:33,000
But, you know, it took pressure to do it. And so, you know, just trying to meet the needs of the communities, what it was all about, you know, and, you know, things of this nature.

708
01:52:33,000 --> 01:52:36,000
So, tremendous amount of work in different programs.

709
01:52:36,000 --> 01:52:42,000
Yeah. You know, you did eventually decide to leave the park.

710
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:47,000
Yeah, well, that kind of happened.

711
01:52:48,000 --> 01:53:02,000
You would do some political differences, I guess, you would call it, in that different things happen with UV.

712
01:53:03,000 --> 01:53:12,000
I think Huey had a dislike for the organization as it were.

713
01:53:12,000 --> 01:53:25,000
And, I never had been sadist, but he dispended all the chapters across the country.

714
01:53:25,000 --> 01:53:44,000
And, I suppose, to bring organizers all into Oakland under the guys of having these people work on the Bobby Seale for Mayor campaign.

715
01:53:44,000 --> 01:54:03,000
And, that was viable, but at the same time, I don't think he wanted to deal with the responsibility of a nationwide organization and all the things that needed, you know, had to be done.

716
01:54:04,000 --> 01:54:27,000
So, in my opinion, he did a disservice to the people who had followed the Panther philosophy and had worked their tales off to develop programs, to gain resources to do that in their communities.

717
01:54:28,000 --> 01:54:37,000
You know, all of a sudden you tell them to close down the chapters and the people in the community that benefited from what happened in those chapters.

718
01:54:37,000 --> 01:54:45,000
So, that was one of my personal criticism of that move.

719
01:54:45,000 --> 01:54:55,000
And, you know, then, of course, people begin to leave and all of that.

720
01:54:55,000 --> 01:55:03,000
And, it got to a point, you know, even Bobby Seale left.

721
01:55:03,000 --> 01:55:22,000
And, without any explanation, that's a wide, but, you know, it was all, you know, a result of due to ramifications of closing the party down, really, if you will.

722
01:55:23,000 --> 01:55:34,000
And, it was a top decision, rank and file, and people like myself had never seen it.

723
01:55:34,000 --> 01:55:41,000
And, I say, well, you know, Bobby Seale left and didn't say goodbye.

724
01:55:42,000 --> 01:55:45,000
You know, it's over, for I'm certain it's over.

725
01:55:45,000 --> 01:56:03,000
And, you know, I think it limped along a little while, where people out of the own self-angrant disment called party and called themselves as a chairman and a new leadership or whatever.

726
01:56:04,000 --> 01:56:12,000
And, you know, Elaine Brown of GIF from Huey.

727
01:56:12,000 --> 01:56:19,000
But, other than that, it was nothing. It was no party.

728
01:56:19,000 --> 01:56:32,000
So, the people that were last minute hangers on who took advantage of what I guess financial resources, they were left over or whatever.

729
01:56:33,000 --> 01:56:44,000
And, using the party's name, because it was out there, to do whatever they wanted to do.

730
01:56:44,000 --> 01:56:53,000
I decided, you know, it's time to go. I fulfilled my mission.

731
01:56:54,000 --> 01:57:07,000
And, you know, time to look for some other things and see if I have any other talents.

732
01:57:08,000 --> 01:57:25,000
And, you know, small group of people came to me and told me, you know, in confidence that, you know, party's over and other people have taken it over.

733
01:57:25,000 --> 01:57:34,000
And, if you want to leave the party, we'll follow you. We'll back you.

734
01:57:35,000 --> 01:57:43,000
And, I said, well, nope. You know, some of the best organizers in this country.

735
01:57:43,000 --> 01:57:57,000
So, you know, you just get out of, out of Oakland and go back to where you, wherever you want, because you have the talent to do whatever you want.

736
01:57:58,000 --> 01:58:04,000
And, I know that. And, if you ever need me for anything, you know what a family.

737
01:58:04,000 --> 01:58:09,000
And, we did that. And, I love.

738
01:58:09,000 --> 01:58:14,000
And, you know, never look back.

739
01:58:14,000 --> 01:58:23,000
Billy X Jennings kept after me for years to participate in reunions and stuff like that.

740
01:58:23,000 --> 01:58:37,000
And, at any time, I went into retail. I got a job without anybody knowing my background. I got a job with Kmart as a citizen manager.

741
01:58:37,000 --> 01:58:40,000
And, worked for them for about 13 years.

742
01:58:40,000 --> 01:58:43,000
You went back to the, to the South?

743
01:58:43,000 --> 01:58:49,000
Yeah. Yeah.

744
01:58:49,000 --> 01:58:54,000
Got sent to some of the town in Virginia to train.

745
01:58:54,000 --> 01:59:00,000
And, they moved you around quite a bit, you know, wherever that you needed.

746
01:59:00,000 --> 01:59:12,000
And, so, I went through their training program and, you know, became successful at that.

747
01:59:12,000 --> 01:59:27,000
And, it afforded me a lot, doing a lot of things that I think that I had done as a panther in terms of being a mentor to young people.

748
01:59:27,000 --> 01:59:34,000
And, people come in and they're working for Kmart for a little or nothing.

749
01:59:34,000 --> 01:59:43,000
And, they would have grievances against a supervisor and stuff like that.

750
01:59:43,000 --> 01:59:50,000
You know, and I have to pull them aside and say, look, you need a job, you need money.

751
01:59:50,000 --> 01:59:58,000
So, just hang in there and don't fly off and do anything that will damage you.

752
01:59:58,000 --> 02:00:02,000
Keep this while you're got it because it's paying you something.

753
02:00:02,000 --> 02:00:09,000
And, you know, I'm going to do what I can to help you.

754
02:00:09,000 --> 02:00:19,000
And, you know, that's how, you know, developed, I think, some young people's character.

755
02:00:19,000 --> 02:00:27,000
And, taught them how to do what was good for them and how to sidestep the snakes that were there to bite them.

756
02:00:27,000 --> 02:00:30,000
And, like that.

757
02:00:30,000 --> 02:00:38,000
And, I went from there, I got, I think I got tired of the place that Kmart sent me.

758
02:00:38,000 --> 02:00:48,000
Yeah, I think it was real North Carolina, I think it was down there where I was crazy G.I.

759
02:00:48,000 --> 02:00:57,000
And, I got a job with an outfit called, a retail outfit called, Service Merchandise.

760
02:00:57,000 --> 02:01:02,000
And, it had a different merchandise and philosophy.

761
02:01:02,000 --> 02:01:10,000
It wasn't so much great, big box stuff and dealing with a whole lot of little stuff.

762
02:01:10,000 --> 02:01:15,000
It was mostly a place where you go and buy gifts.

763
02:01:15,000 --> 02:01:41,000
You know, and I learned this system and went from, you know, I guess a trainee up until I got a point of storm and ran a couple of my own stores.

764
02:01:41,000 --> 02:01:50,000
And, I find that they got to the point where they had different philosophy and their management and stuff like that.

765
02:01:50,000 --> 02:01:53,000
It was pretty much like what's going on now.

766
02:01:53,000 --> 02:01:58,000
You get up to a management where you're making a nice bucket too.

767
02:01:58,000 --> 02:02:10,000
And, then they would fire you and use less person to get the job done.

768
02:02:10,000 --> 02:02:16,000
And, the person at the top would get the damn big bonus, the money that you used to make.

769
02:02:16,000 --> 02:02:27,000
And, so, you know, I gave that up and it was time where I would get close to being able to draw my social security.

770
02:02:27,000 --> 02:02:32,000
So, I'll say, you know, I'm out of it.

771
02:02:32,000 --> 02:02:37,000
Anyway, Billy kept after me, up after me.

772
02:02:37,000 --> 02:02:46,000
And, you finally had one of his reunions in Washington, D.C.

773
02:02:46,000 --> 02:02:50,000
And, I was living in Maryland at the time.

774
02:02:50,000 --> 02:02:58,000
So, I decided to attend and all these old comrades, I thought you were dead.

775
02:02:58,000 --> 02:03:00,000
And, stuff like that.

776
02:03:00,000 --> 02:03:14,000
So, I began to realize, I guess, somewhat that I had a legacy going or whatever.

777
02:03:15,000 --> 02:03:24,000
I began to relate to that and...

778
02:03:24,000 --> 02:03:28,000
You hadn't talked about the Panthers in years, right?

779
02:03:28,000 --> 02:03:29,000
No.

780
02:03:29,000 --> 02:03:31,000
Nobody knew that.

781
02:03:31,000 --> 02:03:34,000
None of those people in retail that I worked with, anything.

782
02:03:34,000 --> 02:03:37,000
I never would have got the job.

783
02:03:37,000 --> 02:03:39,000
Did your children know?

784
02:03:39,000 --> 02:03:41,000
Did your family know?

785
02:03:42,000 --> 02:03:46,000
Well, I guess five of me, your family.

786
02:03:46,000 --> 02:03:48,000
No, I didn't tell them.

787
02:03:48,000 --> 02:03:56,000
Because I had FBI agents go down and talk to my old aunt and try to figure out where I was.

788
02:03:56,000 --> 02:03:59,000
Stuff like that.

789
02:03:59,000 --> 02:04:02,000
And she said, well, I don't know.

790
02:04:03,000 --> 02:04:06,000
And then I was in some story in Virginia.

791
02:04:06,000 --> 02:04:10,000
A couple of suits came, called me.

792
02:04:10,000 --> 02:04:14,000
Can we talk here outside?

793
02:04:14,000 --> 02:04:17,000
We don't want to jeopardize or stop anything.

794
02:04:17,000 --> 02:04:20,000
And then they're handing me a packet.

795
02:04:20,000 --> 02:04:29,000
And there was something from the Freedom of Information Act from Washington.

796
02:04:30,000 --> 02:04:36,000
It was a whole lot of shit that they had accumulated on me.

797
02:04:36,000 --> 02:04:43,000
And it took a black matter of marker and marked out anything that I could suit her as for.

798
02:04:43,000 --> 02:04:48,000
So I keep this on my archive.

799
02:04:49,000 --> 02:04:55,000
And you know,

800
02:04:55,000 --> 02:05:05,000
but then I had a kid too, and 1980, daughter.

801
02:05:05,000 --> 02:05:14,000
And I kept myself under wraps from her because I knew that the government had no shame.

802
02:05:14,000 --> 02:05:20,000
They would fuck with her to get to me if they could.

803
02:05:20,000 --> 02:05:31,000
So seeing no anything about that until she was, I guess, 16 or 17 or something.

804
02:05:31,000 --> 02:05:40,000
And that's when I finally relented and went to one of the reunions that Billy had kept after me to go to.

805
02:05:41,000 --> 02:05:43,000
And it was in Washington, D.C.

806
02:05:43,000 --> 02:05:46,000
And I was living in Maryland at the time.

807
02:05:46,000 --> 02:05:51,000
So it was an easy place to get to and stuff.

808
02:05:51,000 --> 02:05:55,000
And that's when I went on these people.

809
02:05:55,000 --> 02:05:57,000
I know what happened here.

810
02:05:57,000 --> 02:05:59,000
I thought you dead.

811
02:05:59,000 --> 02:06:01,000
So full of things.

812
02:06:01,000 --> 02:06:04,000
Now I'm here.

813
02:06:05,000 --> 02:06:16,000
And you know, from then on, my daughter got up to age where none of this stuff would affect her.

814
02:06:16,000 --> 02:06:24,000
Then I began to let her know about that.

815
02:06:24,000 --> 02:06:32,000
You know, send her stuff, old stories, things like that.

816
02:06:33,000 --> 02:06:38,000
So nobody could harm her about for anything that I'd done.

817
02:06:38,000 --> 02:06:42,000
So it's kind of where that went.

818
02:06:42,000 --> 02:06:47,000
I could just ask you know what it's been like now that you are telling your story and what you want to accomplish with it.

819
02:06:47,000 --> 02:06:50,000
What kind of feedback you're getting from people.

820
02:06:50,000 --> 02:07:01,000
Oh, I'm getting a tremendous amount of feedback because, you know, everywhere you go, you know, the legacy following here.

821
02:07:02,000 --> 02:07:04,000
Pretty much.

822
02:07:04,000 --> 02:07:19,000
And you're getting to have a deal with people and trying to address some of the same issues that you were addressing before.

823
02:07:19,000 --> 02:07:25,000
That somehow, me, anyway, I can't help but become involved.

824
02:07:26,000 --> 02:07:37,000
So I came back to California after I had moved around the South for a while and stuff.

825
02:07:37,000 --> 02:07:46,000
And I reconnected with Carol, who's, you know, nurse.

826
02:07:46,000 --> 02:07:49,000
I've been a nurse for years and years.

827
02:07:49,000 --> 02:07:56,000
And anyway, I didn't know what it was, but some physical ailments.

828
02:07:56,000 --> 02:08:01,000
It turned out to be prostate cancer.

829
02:08:01,000 --> 02:08:08,000
So here in California, you know, I got the best treatment for that that I could get.

830
02:08:08,000 --> 02:08:14,000
And, but anyways, I didn't think up here.

831
02:08:14,000 --> 02:08:19,000
That was any kind of political repression that I found out very differently.

832
02:08:19,000 --> 02:08:33,000
Because you had a combination of state troopers, county shares, and local police forces that were killing people.

833
02:08:33,000 --> 02:08:40,000
And people were all up and armed about what to do about it.

834
02:08:40,000 --> 02:08:48,000
So, you know, naturally I had to get involved in it.

835
02:08:48,000 --> 02:08:54,000
And so we had big meetings and stuff like that.

836
02:08:54,000 --> 02:08:59,000
And people were, you know, just really at the witch's end.

837
02:08:59,000 --> 02:09:01,000
It's what to do about that.

838
02:09:01,000 --> 02:09:10,000
And then we also had the immigration problem with the ICE and stuff.

839
02:09:10,000 --> 02:09:18,000
So we began to get together with these people and try to iron out something that we could do.

840
02:09:18,000 --> 02:09:24,000
And so we had big meetings and held some works out and so forth.

841
02:09:24,000 --> 02:09:39,000
So out of the works out that I held, we came up with the idea of creating a help line for people who had no records

842
02:09:39,000 --> 02:09:42,000
when they were abused by the cops and so forth.

843
02:09:42,000 --> 02:09:51,000
And we called it the PACH.

844
02:09:51,000 --> 02:10:01,000
And we established like a 24-hour telephone line where people can call and make a report.

845
02:10:01,000 --> 02:10:06,000
And we would take that report and put it on the database.

846
02:10:06,000 --> 02:10:16,000
And at some point people wanted to file a suit against police or whatever we could go to that database

847
02:10:16,000 --> 02:10:21,000
and provide that information form to take the court or whatever.

848
02:10:21,000 --> 02:10:24,000
And so that's still going.

849
02:10:25,000 --> 02:10:35,000
And so, you know, there's always, you know, and there's issues that come up that to me you can't ignore.

850
02:10:35,000 --> 02:10:43,000
I really upsetting as they killed 13-year-old Andy Lopez, cops shot him in the back.

851
02:10:43,000 --> 02:10:48,000
He was walking his own neighborhood in the middle of the day, not bothering anybody.

852
02:10:48,000 --> 02:10:58,000
And he had a toy weapon that this cop that sat him said it looked like an assault rifle.

853
02:10:58,000 --> 02:11:07,000
But you can tell how acute carries heavy weapon as to a toy.

854
02:11:07,000 --> 02:11:11,000
And so they opened up with him and all they did was shout at him.

855
02:11:12,000 --> 02:11:15,000
And for the words, got out of their mouth.

856
02:11:15,000 --> 02:11:20,000
They opened up and shouted for about seven or eight times and killed him.

857
02:11:20,000 --> 02:11:28,000
So that became an age issue and created, you know, demonstrations and stuff.

858
02:11:28,000 --> 02:11:36,000
And the bad part about it is that Sheriff Deputy was not indicted.

859
02:11:37,000 --> 02:11:40,000
And he was put back on the job, put back on the street.

860
02:11:40,000 --> 02:11:47,000
And, you know, that, you know, so it seemed like it never ended.

861
02:11:47,000 --> 02:11:54,000
Since that happened, we had all these other killers.

862
02:11:54,000 --> 02:12:03,000
You know, just endless names of, you know, scoring, re-rooting back to,

863
02:12:03,000 --> 02:12:10,000
you know, for the reason they called this, called this the organ act, you know.

864
02:12:10,000 --> 02:12:27,000
And, you know, so I, you know, involved as much as I can, we're not meant to, you know,

865
02:12:27,000 --> 02:12:41,000
criticism, the DA and the county prosecutor and all those people give a voice to the people.

866
02:12:41,000 --> 02:12:45,000
So the fight continues.

867
02:12:45,000 --> 02:12:47,000
So it continues.

868
02:12:47,000 --> 02:12:49,000
Absolutely.

869
02:12:49,000 --> 02:12:57,000
You know, so, you know, I don't know, some of the people in the Civil Rights Movement could quit.

870
02:12:57,000 --> 02:13:07,000
And I guess get wealthy, I get rich and find their peace and their heaven and that.

871
02:13:07,000 --> 02:13:10,000
Not me, I'm not so blessed.

872
02:13:10,000 --> 02:13:12,000
I got to keep fighting.

873
02:13:13,000 --> 02:13:15,000
Well, we have to end there, I'm afraid.

874
02:13:15,000 --> 02:13:18,000
So let me just say thank you.

875
02:13:18,000 --> 02:13:21,000
Thank you for all of your work over the years.

876
02:13:21,000 --> 02:13:24,000
And, uh, there's a horrible story now.

877
02:13:24,000 --> 02:13:27,000
Talk about what's an important story.

878
02:13:27,000 --> 02:13:36,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

